The better world is already here
KOPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to plunder and war, and in which the growing production capacity of recent decades leads to more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, has influenced the environmental movement up to today.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
Von ihren Gegnern werden sie als „Ökonomen des Überflusses“ gesehen, die dem Markt vertrauen, der angeblich alle Probleme löst.
Aber statt Tatsachen und Geschichten herauszupicken, die in eine große Erzählung von Niedergang oder Fortschritt passen, sollten wir versuchen, alle Bereiche der menschlichen Existenz zu vergleichen, um zu sehen, ob die Welt wirklich besser oder schlechter wird.
Genau dies habe ich gemeinsam mit 21 weltweit führenden Ökonomen dadurch zu erreichen versucht, dass wir eine Wertungsliste der letzten 150 Jahre entwickelten.
In zehn Bereichen – darunter Gesundheit, Ausbildung, Krieg, Geschlechterverhältnis, Luftverschmutzung, Klimaveränderung und Biodiversität – haben die Ökonomen alle dieselbe Frage beantwortet: Wie hoch waren die relativen Kosten dieses Problems in jedem Jahr von 1900 bis 2013, einschließlich Prognosen bis 2050.
Anhand klassischer ökonomischer Bewertungen aller Faktoren von Todesopfern, Gesundheitsschäden und Analphabetentum über die Zerstörung von Feuchtgebieten bis hin zu höherem Hurrikan-Risiko durch globale Erwärmung zeigen die Ökonomen die Kosten jedes einzelnen Problems auf.
To assess the scale of the problem, it is compared with the overall available resources for its solution.
Thus, the size of the problem becomes clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let us consider the gender inequality.
Basically, we excluded almost half of the world population from production back then.
1900 were only 15% of the global workforce female.
What are the losses resulting from this low proportion?
Even when we take into account the higher costs of educating women and the fact that someone must carry out unpaid housework, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female employment rate and smaller income differences, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is probably very surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring largely a growing net benefit – rising up to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits prevail.
On the one hand, the higher entries of CO2 were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more cold-related deaths than it causes additional heat-related deaths.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, which corresponds to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, with further rising temperatures, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, which dramatically reduces the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the value list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in the year 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators have improved the most around the world.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy hardly changed.
The size of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and by 2050 it is likely to be 76 years).
The biggest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
For example, in 1970 only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved in the entire 20th century through world peace.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and have promised another 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of Polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the cost of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to surprising 32% of the world's GDP.
Today they have dropped to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Even though optimists are not right on all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century likely costs about 1% of GDP annually, and significantly more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically declined.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no problems left.
Although they have become smaller in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should start getting used to the idea that the world has improved significantly.
In addition, the ranking shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view of the future towards the worst stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather towards objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
